>Advice for new runners
- Try to keep your cadence high (at or around 180 steps per minute)
- Try to keep your heartrate in Zone1/2 (around an average of 55-65% of your max. heart rate)
- Build up speed and mileage SLOOOOWLY (start with 15 minutes, increase time/mileage by 10% per week)
- Yes, it will feel like you're going slow, you are; don't worry about setting good times for at least a couple months

>Who is /fat/ for?
For fatties who are working towards a better physique through meaningful hard-work, strategy, and dedication. This is not QTDDTOT, stick to questions on fat loss. Post height and weight when asking for advice.
Join our Fatty Contest: https://www.fattycontest.com/

>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

>Now what?
Count calories, all of them.
Eat about 500-1000 less calories than your TDEE.
Buy scales, be accurate.
Learn to cook. Try to stick to lean protein and green vegetables.
Eat a lot of protein. 0.72g per lb of goal lean body mass.
Doing cardio, even just walking, will improve your health. There is no such thing as a healthy fat heart, but you can offset the risks.
Lifting weights will keep and gain muscle mass and burn fat much quicker. No lifting results in the body burning away muscle AND fat.
Drink more water.
Read the /fit/ sticky: https://liamrosen.com/fitness.html

>DON'T
Eat refined sugars, they're terrible for you regardless of calories.
Eat processed foods.
Drink your calories (alcohol, soda, starbucks).
Freak out over a weight loss stall. Plateaus can last up to three weeks.
"Reward" yourself. Cheat days cheat only yourself.

>Other resources:
Loose skin, gyno & stretch marks: https://weight-loss-side-effects.netlify.app/
Reddit wiki: https://www.reddit.com/r/loseit/wiki/faq

>fatigue
You're misusing that term, at least in weightlifting terms. Fatigue is what you build up over time, across multiple sessions. It's when you start to feel like you're not recovering, tired all the time, like you can't lift at maximum capacity. It's caused by a combination of accumulated muscle damage, depleted glycogen and nutrient stores, and disrupted hormones. Generally it can be cleared through better sleep and/or diet, or by taking a deload.
>I feel like terminating the set, throwing up and leaving the gym after the first 3/12 reps on pullups or leg presses or whatever.
What you seem to be talking about is poor conditioning. You lack the capacity to sustain maximum intensity for any time and get gassed very quickly. After a few heavy reps you've used up all your fuel stores and your body isn't capable of replenishing them quickly enough. The best fix is probably to add in some high intensity stuff - kettlebell swings, burpees, sprints or sled pushes. Stuff that really gets your heart rate up and leaves you gasping for breath.

If you don't enjoy lifting more for the sake of it, you aren't gonna make it. Don't need discipline when you want to be in the gym because you need there to be able to lift more than the last session, the week or month before etc.', 'time': 1670913408, 'resto': 69241276}, {'no': 69241679, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)01:43:09', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': 'A journal where I plan my day in split of 50 minute blocks with 10 minute pauses.I pencil it in.', 'time': 1670913789, 'resto': 69241276}, {'no': 69242663, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:17:24', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>69241358
Go away shlomo', 'time': 1670926644, 'resto': 69241276}, {'no': 69242762, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:31:51', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>69241276
The hard days are when I don't want to do it. Those are the days where I have to use force of will to get my ass out of the couch. It's awful, but then when I'm at the gym and already got a couple sets in, I feel alright. If I don't, then I will finish my routine without pushing myself further than I need to. I showed up. That's what counts. You just gotta show up.

The good news is that after a while, it gets easier. Most days I am happy to go to the gym. I find myself at work thinking "Oh, what am I going to do this evening at the gym? Chest? Awesome, can't wait". It's a part of my day that helps me relax mentally. I make sure to turn off notifications and close all apps on my phone when I enter the gym. It's a moment to reflect upon my day, to consider my achievements and failures, and to be better. These good days are the days where I push hard. Where after near-failure on a set, I feel good and strong.

To more you do it, the more often you have good days and less bad days. But I don't think the bad days ever get eradicated for good. Even the swolest guys have days where they don't really wanna work out or do anything. They just do it even if they don't want to. They show up. You just gotta show up. Every day.

Having someone to keep you accountable also helps. For me it's my gf. We live together. I remember when I started going gym, one evening I was so tired and I didn't really want to go. After a while she asked me "aren't you going to workout today?". I said "not really, I'm too tired. I'm going to rest today" and made up a bunch of excuses. The look of disappointment on her face made me angry. So I got up off my ass and went to work out. I thank her for that. She pushes me to be better every day.', 'time': 1670927511, 'resto': 69241276}, {'no': 69242795, 'now': '12/13/22(Tue)05:36:37', 'name': 'Anonymous', 'com': '>>69242762

If you don't have a gf, maybe ask a friend to keep you accountable, even if he or she doesn't work out. Having someone that asks you every day "hey! how did workout go?" is really helpful. Making excuses to yourself in your head isn't the same as making excuses to others. You may be able to convince yourself inside your head because you've been doing it all your life. Convincing or lying to others is not so easy - that's when you realize your excuses are bullshit and don't really make sense.

If you don't have any friends then maybe join a discord group. Hell, maybe even find a way to use this board to your advantage. I dunno, figure something out. Keep a journal. Mark it on a calendar. Whatever.

Anyways. Good luck, OP.', 'time': 1670927797, 'resto': 69241276}]
